# üîç ALTERNATIVE APPROACH: .htaccess file (NOT USED in this lab)
# This shows how the same configuration would look using .htaccess
# For educational purposes only

AuthType Basic
AuthName "Acesso Restrito ao Teste"
AuthUserFile /etc/htpasswd/.htpasswd
Require valid-user

# ============================================================
# .htaccess vs Directory Directive Comparison:
# ============================================================
# 
# USING .htaccess (this file):
# ------------------------------------------
# Location: /var/www/html/teste/.htaccess
# Requires: AllowOverride AuthConfig in main Apache config
# Pros: 
#   - Can be modified without restarting Apache
#   - Useful when you don't have access to main config
# Cons:
#   - Slower (Apache checks for .htaccess on every request)
#   - Less secure (file in web-accessible directory)
#   - Harder to manage (configs scattered)
#
# USING DIRECTIVE (what we actually used):
# ------------------------------------------
# Location: /etc/apache2/sites-available/000-default.conf  
# Pros:
#   - Faster (no filesystem checks on every request)
#   - More secure (config in protected directory)
#   - Centralized management
#   - Better for production environments
# Cons:
#   - Requires Apache restart for changes
#   - Needs server configuration access
#
# ============================================================
# LEARNING OUTCOME:
# ============================================================
# This lab demonstrates the industry-preferred approach of using
# Directory directives in Virtual Host configuration files rather
# than .htaccess files, following Apache security best practices.
